prove exactly who had shot the plane down and with what type of missile.

00:07:20.076 --> 00:07:26.316
Higgins got to work, and through a series of images he managed to track down on social media

00:07:26.586 --> 00:07:33.476
he found a video of a missile launcher travelling through Russia in a military convoy, then

00:07:33.626 --> 00:07:40.456
he found another video of it in Ukraine returning to Russia with one missile missing from it.

00:07:41.686 --> 00:07:42.236
Bingo.

00:07:42.952 --> 00:07:49.935
Higgins had managed, from the comfort of his home in England and completely on his own, what none

00:07:50.195 --> 00:07:56.285
of the multi-million dollar intelligence agencies in Europe and the United States had managed.

00:07:57.205 --> 00:07:59.105
And the successes continued.

00:07:59.515 --> 00:08:03.775
Bellingcat exposed the Syrian government’s use of chemical weapons

00:08:04.015 --> 00:08:08.445
during the Syrian war, and the use of drones to kill civilians.

00:08:09.405 --> 00:08:16.075
And Higgins was not afraid to shine a light on the actions of Western governments as well.

00:08:17.265 --> 00:08:23.995
On March 16, 2017, a bomb was dropped on a mosque in Aleppo, Syria,

00:08:24.275 --> 00:08:28.235
killing over 50 people who were there for the evening prayer.

00:08:29.305 --> 00:08:35.935
Most posts on social media and news stories blamed the Syrian government or Russia,

00:08:36.525 --> 00:08:43.995
but after trawling through images and videos of the event, of satellite imagery and of

00:08:44.005 --> 00:08:50.635
thousands of other images of similar attacks, Bellingcat provided very compelling evidence

00:08:50.875 --> 00:08:56.885
that it was actually the Pentagon, the US military that was responsible for the attack.

00:08:58.045 --> 00:09:04.045
The biggest scoop to date, the biggest success story for Bellingcat, was still to come.

00:09:04.645 --> 00:09:12.385
On 4th March 2018, Sergei Skripal, a former Russian secret service agent,

00:09:12.675 --> 00:09:17.325
and his daughter Yulia, were poisoned with the nerve-agent Novichock,

00:09:17.715 --> 00:09:22.585
while living in the otherwise very sleepy English town of Salisbury.

00:09:23.263 --> 00:09:28.175
Skripal had been a double-agent for the British, he had been passing information

00:09:28.445 --> 00:09:34.175
to the British secret service in the 1990s, and had spent six years in Russian

00:09:34.215 --> 00:09:40.525
prison before being allowed to move to the UK, where he lived a very quiet life.

00:09:41.575 --> 00:09:45.915
When Skripal and his daughter were poisoned, the finger was immediately

00:09:45.915 --> 00:09:50.675
pointed at Russia, and really, to the man at the top, Vladimir Putin.

00:09:51.735 --> 00:09:58.055
The poison was quickly identified as Novichok, a poison developed in Russia in the

00:09:58.225 --> 00:10:05.185
1980s, and one that was known to be used by the GRU, the Russian secret service agency.

00:10:06.025 --> 00:10:10.995
It’s almost as if Putin wanted to make this very clear that this was

00:10:10.995 --> 00:10:15.975
a state-sponsored murder and it wouldn’t have been the first time.

00:10:16.735 --> 00:10:20.005
Another Russian ex-secret service agent, Alexander

00:10:20.005 --> 00:10:24.985
Litvinenko, had been poisoned with polonium in 2006.

00:10:26.025 --> 00:10:33.655
Litvinenko had become an enemy of the Russian state, and had fled to London in a bid to stay alive.

00:10:34.255 --> 00:10:39.205
But, he was murdered, poisoned, and in fact died in the hospital

00:10:39.355 --> 00:10:42.685
next to my former university, University College London.

00:10:43.515 --> 00:10:48.795
With the poisoning of Litvinenko and of Skripal it’s believed that Putin wanted to

00:10:48.795 --> 00:10:54.275
send a message to any other Russian secret service agent that was thinking of betraying

00:10:54.275 --> 00:11:00.095
their country that you couldn’t hide - eventually you would be found and murdered.

00:11:01.255 --> 00:11:07.842
Skripal and his daughter were rushed to hospital, but unlike Litvinenko, they recovered.

00:11:08.642 --> 00:11:12.552
Of course, this was a major diplomatic incident.

00:11:12.872 --> 00:11:16.242
There was an attempted double murder on British soil,

00:11:16.462 --> 00:11:19.712
and a foreign state was thought to be responsible.

00:11:20.802 --> 00:11:27.692
In August of that year, after all diplomatic avenues had been exhausted, the then British Prime

00:11:27.692 --> 00:11:34.422
Minister, Theresa May, published the faces and names of the two men that British Intelligence

00:11:34.422 --> 00:11:42.802
forces believed had carried out the attack: Ruslan Boshirov and Alexander Petrov, but saying

00:11:42.812 --> 00:11:48.112
that it was believed that these names were pseudonyms, that they weren’t their real names.

00:11:48.832 --> 00:11:55.522
With the photos and names of these two men now publicly available, Bellingcat got to work.

00:11:56.352 --> 00:12:01.892
The Bellingcat team had by then expanded dramatically, and consisted

00:12:02.042 --> 00:12:06.862
of both full-time employees and volunteers, people like me or you

00:12:07.132 --> 00:12:11.282
armed only with an internet connection and desire to seek the truth.

00:12:12.092 --> 00:12:16.932
They had the images of the two men, so they had a broad age range.

00:12:17.472 --> 00:12:21.402
This meant they must have attended military school during a

00:12:21.402 --> 00:12:25.572
particular period, and would likely have trained in Siberia.

00:12:26.482 --> 00:12:31.712
Bellingcat went through databases of graduates of military schools, looked

00:12:31.722 --> 00:12:37.232
through photos, yearbooks, and called up other students to ask for information.

00:12:38.002 --> 00:12:43.702
They also managed to buy a black-market database of Russian passport

00:12:43.722 --> 00:12:49.272
information - copies of which are reportedly pretty easy and cheap to find online.

00:12:50.322 --> 00:12:56.342
They managed to find a match - they found a man named Colonel Anatoliy Chepiga,

00:12:56.892 --> 00:13:01.572
whose photo directly matched the photo of the man spotted in Salisbury.

00:13:02.632 --> 00:13:06.002
Shortly after they managed to track down the other man

00:13:06.233 --> 00:13:10.123
from sources as varied as a car insurance database.

00:13:10.643 --> 00:13:12.773
They identified him as Dr.

00:13:12.823 --> 00:13:18.553
Alexander Yevgeniyevich Mishkin, and they knew they were onto something when they

00:13:18.553 --> 00:13:23.783
called up ex-classmates of Mishkin’s who revealed that they had been contacted

00:13:23.833 --> 00:13:29.423
by Russian authorities and instructed not to reveal any information about him.

00:13:30.073 --> 00:13:37.833
Both Mishkin and Chepiga were GRU agents, and they were a perfect match for the attempted murderers.

00:13:38.763 --> 00:13:43.903
Again, Bellingcat and its team of amateurs and volunteers had managed

00:13:43.913 --> 00:13:48.863
to do what the multi-million pound British intelligence services hadn’t.

00:13:49.753 --> 00:13:57.133
A slightly comic turn in this story is that, despite being caught red handed, Mishkin and Chepiga,

00:13:57.553 --> 00:14:04.323
still using their pseudonyms of Ruslan Boshirov and Alexander Petrov, were interviewed by Russian

00:14:04.323 --> 00:14:10.703
state TV, where they claimed that they were friends in the fitness industry who had travelled

00:14:10.713 --> 00:14:18.043
directly to Salisbury from Moscow to in order to visit the cathedral and its famous 123 metre spire.

00:14:18.813 --> 00:14:22.913
They weren’t very good assassins, but they were even worse actors.

00:14:23.713 --> 00:14:30.233
The Skripal saga was a real turning point for Bellingcat, and for the citizen journalism movement.

00:14:30.993 --> 00:14:37.063
When Bellingcat first started it was looked down on as a group of eccentric

00:14:37.073 --> 00:14:42.093
hobbyists, people who liked problem-solving and were harmless, but weren’t

00:14:42.103 --> 00:14:46.723
really going to have any impact on the way information gathering was done.

00:14:47.323 --> 00:14:52.763
After the successes with the Malaysian airline, the Syrian civil war, multiple

00:14:52.813 --> 00:14:58.473
other smaller successes and now catching the Russian state engaging in attempted

00:14:58.473 --> 00:15:04.273
murder on foreign soil, the power of the citizen detective was clear for all to see.

00:15:05.363 --> 00:15:11.513
And since 2011, since Eliot Higgins decided to take an interest in the Civil War,

00:15:12.023 --> 00:15:17.773
numerous technological advances have made the life of the citizen detective much easier.

00:15:18.663 --> 00:15:23.953
For starters, every single day, more and more information is shared online.

00:15:24.503 --> 00:15:30.503
From photos, videos, hacked databases, social media posts, the more information

00:15:30.503 --> 00:15:35.593
that’s available online, the more evidence that is for the citizen detective.

00:15:36.063 --> 00:15:40.663
Bellingcat actually publicly releases a step-by-step account

00:15:40.863 --> 00:15:45.953
of exactly how it goes through evidence, and it’s fascinating.

00:15:46.373 --> 00:15:50.753
I’d definitely recommend you reading it - it’s all available on their

00:15:50.773 --> 00:15:56.343
website, bellingcat.com, and there are some excellent resources for how you

00:15:56.343 --> 00:16:00.413
can take part, if that's the sort of thing that sounds interesting to you.

00:16:01.343 --> 00:16:06.543
For example, if an original image file is available, there is lots of

00:16:06.563 --> 00:16:11.523
information that can come attached with it, such as the date and time

00:16:11.523 --> 00:16:15.763
the image was taken, the location, and the device it was taken on.

00:16:16.483 --> 00:16:21.023
Google Maps and Google Street View are both excellent resources, of course,

00:16:21.153 --> 00:16:26.573
and when combined with Google Earth and other satellite imagery this allows

00:16:26.653 --> 00:16:31.293
citizen detectives to accurately locate where events have taken place.

00:16:32.023 --> 00:16:37.993
